                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d217">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.48 Refugees/4935: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-04">January 4,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>53. Concerning IGC mandate referred to in your 9111 December 31, Department
                    accepts statement prepared by Emerson. However if statement is published
                    inclusion of last sentence might raise new controversy and it seems preferable
                    to omit it. At present we have no intention to publish Emerson’s statement but
                    we may desire to do so at any time omitting last sentence.<note n="26"
                        xml:id="d217fn26">Telegram No. 135, January 6, 1944, from the Ambassador in
                        the United Kingdom indicated that there was no objection to publishing
                        Emerson’s statement in the United States, omitting the last sentence (840.48
                        Refugees/4962).</note> There is no objection here if statement is published
                    in London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
